If generating equals() for a class without an equals() method it is correct:
  @Override
  public boolean equals(Object obj) {
    if (this == obj) return true;
    if (obj == null) return false;
    if (getClass() != obj.getClass()) return false;
    final Abc other = (Abc) obj;
    if (i != other.i) return false;
    return true;
  }

But if an equals() allready exists and check to overwrite equals is wrong:

  @Override
  public boolean equals(Object obj) {
    if (this == obj) return true;
    if (!super.equals(obj)) return false;
    if (getClass() != obj.getClass()) return false;
    final Abc other = (Abc) obj;
    if (i != other.i) return false;
    return true;
  }

The class is a direct subclass of Object an therefore super.equals() shouldn't be called.

