20061115

In the following scenario a class A extends B from an other (required) project but hasn't interface 'I' on the classpath which is implemented by B.

The compiler issues an error on 'A extends B', but not on 'new B()'.


- project A, requires project B
   public class A extends B { // error here
      {
        B b= new B() {}; // no error here
      }
   }
- project B, requires C
   public abstract class B implements I {
   }
- project C:
   public interface I {
   }

Released MultiProjectTests # 102 and 103.

Consider the alternative test case with same projects, same dependencies, same sources except A.java:
   public class A {
      {
        B b= new B() {}; // a
        B c= new B() {};
      }
   }

We then report the error of line a against the beginning of the file, once only.

I believe that this is a deliberate attempt to provide a single, useful buildpath error.

Note that javac does almost the same, reporting only once in both cases, but reporting against line a while we report against line 1 (which IMHO has the advantage of making the error more prominent than buried deep into the file).

I would then contend that this works as designed.

All generated diagrams use the default preferences, which include turning on anti-aliasing.  Thus, unless you specifically disable anti-aliasing within your diagram code, you will experience these issues in your generated diagrams.

You can disable anti aliasing in your GMF editor by updating the XXXPreferenceInitializer class and overriding the initializeDefaultPreferences method.

public void initializeDefaultPreferences() {
   super.initializeDefaultPreferences();
   getPreferenceStore().setValue(IPreferenceConstants.PREF_ENABLE_ANTIALIAS, false);
}

